Ten Rules of Bad Studying
========================================================

```{r, echo=FALSE}
library(RColorBrewer)
library(wordcloud)
library(tm)

colors1 <- brewer.pal(9, "Greens")
palette1 <- colorRampPalette(colors1)
colors2 <- brewer.pal(9, "YlOrRd")
palette2 <- colorRampPalette(colors2)

datasetInput <- data.frame(
        Name = c("Passive Rereading",
                 "Highlights",
                 "Glancing",
                 "Last Minute",
                 "Same Problems",
                 "Friend Chats",
                 "Neglect Textbook",
                 "Unclear",
                 "Distractions",
                 "Lack Sleep"),
        Value = c(3,4,5,3,3,4,2,5,6,4), stringsAsFactors=FALSE)

wordcloud(datasetInput$Name, datasetInput$Value, scale=c(5,1), 
          max.words=100, random.order=TRUE, random.color=FALSE,
          rot.per=0.5, use.r.layout=FALSE, colors=colors2)
```

Ten Rules of Bad Studying
========================================================
1. Passive rereading
- Letting highlights overwhelm you
- Merely glancing at a problemâ€™s solution and thinking you know how to do it
- Waiting until the last minute to study
- Repeatedly solving problems of the same type that you already know how to solve
- Letting study sessions with friends turn into chat sessions
- Neglecting to read the textbook before you start working problems
- Not checking with your instructors or classmates to clear up points of confusion
- Thinking you can learn deeply when you are being constantly distracted
- Not getting enough sleep

